<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma Views on Restructuring Economy, Crimea Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma Views on Restructuring Economy, Crimea Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106214494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 2004 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A candidate for the Ukrainian presidency, Leonid 
Kuchma, has said that his first step in the office would be to 
reconstruct 90 percent of Ukraine's enterprises like West 
Germany is doing in East Germany. Speaking at a news conference 
in Kiev Wednesday [1 June], he pointed out that he pinned his 
hopes on private foreign capital rather than centralized western 
aid in the resolution of economic issues. 
  "We have no hope for a Marshall plan, that is why Ukraine 
should rely on its own forces in the first place," Kuchma was 
quoted as saying. He added that it was necessary to create such 
rules of the games that western partners did not fear to lose 
their investments. 
  Commenting on his initiative to grant Crimea special status 
announced in parliament Wednesday, Kuchma said he meant the 
status of a free economic area. It is necessary to give Crimea 
more economic independence rather than take back powers, he said 
adding that Crimea should be kept within the Ukrainian state 
borders,. 
  The presidential elections in Ukraine will be held on 26 
June. 
  Leonid Kuchma is Ukraine's former prime minister, presently 
the president of the Ukrainian Industrialists and Entrepreneurs' 
Union and the leader of the Interregional Bloc for Reforms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

