<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Solzhenitsyn Seen as Possible Presidential Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Solzhenitsyn Seen as Possible Presidential Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106190994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1541 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0106190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Democratic and centrist forces may support a single 
candidate, renowned writer Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn, at the next 
presidential elections in Russia, one of the Democratic Russia 
movement leaders supposed. 
  A co-chairman of Democratic Russia, priest Gleb Yakunin told 
Interfax Wednesday that "all democratic and centrist forces must 
unite to nominate a single candidate for the presidency, 
otherwise a nationwide disaster will happen." 
  In his opinion, such politicians as Yegor Gaydar, Grigoriy 
Yavlinskiy or Sergey Shakhray have very little chance of winning 
the presidential elections in 1996, as all of them are inferior 
to Solzhenitsyn. 
  At the same time, Yakunin said he was concerned and worried 
over some of the statements by Solzhenitsyn who had returned to 
Russia last month after a 20-year exile with respect to the 
national policy and the "Gaydar-Chubays line in the 
implementation of economic reforms." 
  However, Solzhenitsyn's point of view may change as he gets 
to know Russian reality. 
  According to the Russian Constitution, a citizen residing in 
Russia for no fewer than ten years may be elected as president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38803 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov106_c_94001" </HT>


