<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Curfew Imposed on Chechen Republic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Curfew Imposed on Chechen Republic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106161894 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1500 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A curfew has been introduced throughout the Chechen 
Republic from today by presidential decree. Groznyy says that 
the reason for this decision is that Russia has extended the 
state of emergency zone in Ingushetia and North Osetia to cover 
regions which are directly adjacent to Chechnya. 
  Russia has not yet officially proposed holding summit talks 
with the Chechen Republic. The only knowledge we have of a 
possible meeting between Boris Yeltin and Dzhokar Dudayev is 
what we have read in the press. This was stated to our radio 
station by Chechnya's Deputy Prime Minister Mayrabek Mugadayev. 
He stressed that Groznyy does not even know who precisely in 
Moscow is engaged in preparing the summit talks. And any other 
talks, at government or Foreign Ministry level, will not do any 
good, Mugadayev considers. The Russian prime minister also 
agrees with this point of view. 
  [Begin Mugadayev recording] Viktor Stepanovich 
[Chernomyrdin] 
told me straight: He said he approved all seven points or 
questions which we put forward and the draft agreement which I 
showed him. It is necessary for Presidents Yeltsin and Dudayev 
to resolve the political aspect of the question. One can regard 
the government-level talks as having been completed since the 
governments have no complaints against each other. [end 
recording] 
  [Announcer] And here is another report from Groznyy. Dzhokar 
Dudayev today stated that the Russian special services are 
preparing a plan to organize a local nuclear explosion in 
Chechnya. Representatives of Russia's foreign intellignece 
service have denied this report. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

