<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Uzbek Presidents Discuss Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Uzbek Presidents Discuss Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306084794 Tashkent Radio Tashkent Network in Uzbek 0730 
GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tashkent Radio Tashkent Network </F>
<F P=105>  Uzbek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The presidents of the three republics in Central 
Asia, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan will hold a [words 
indistinct] During the summit, questions on economic 
cooperation will be examined. Bolat Ahmadgaliyev, from the 
Kazakh president's office, spoke about this to journalists. It 
is known that after the breakdown of the former [Soviet] Union 
the leaders of the Central Asian republics took a number of 
steps to begin cooperation in the economic field and in many 
other fields. The difficulties of transferring to a market 
economy, leaving the problems of monetary unity in the republics 
untackled, the breakdown of economic ties, and other reasons 
hindered the process of economic cooperation between the Central 
Asian republics from fully forging ahead. 
  The situation has now changed. The problems in the process 
of development are now clear. If Uzbekistan is to introduce its 
own national currency in July then another possibility will be 
found. The cooperation now taking shape between the republics of 
Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan must be expanded. The 
meetings between the leaders of the three republics have started 
to show results, particularly in the economic field. 
  At their scheduled summit meeting the presidents of the 
three 
countries will examine the possibilities of expanding 
cooperation in the agro-industrial field and providing for 
capital and labor forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

