<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on ROK President Kim's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on ROK President Kim's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Yeltsin on DPRK Treaty </H4>

<F P=102> LD0206134494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1324 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Aleksandr Kopnov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 2 TASS -- In two years' time, Russia, by 
all appearances, will not prolong the treaty of friendship, 
cooperation and mutual help signed by the former USSR and 
People's Democratic Republic of Korea in 1961 for another five 
years, a high-ranking official quoted Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin as saying at a meeting with South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam. 
  In accordance with generally recognized norms, the treaty 
may 
be denounced at one year's notice, the source quoted Yeltsin as 
saying. 
  The treaty does exist so far. However, Russia interprets its 
first article, which provides for offering North Korea military 
help automatically, if a war breaks out in the Korean peninsula, 
in a somewhat different way. This provision is actually 
ineffective, Yeltsin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38821 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov107_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on ROK President Kim's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on ROK President Kim's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Seoul Reports Treaty Nonrenewal </H4>

<F P=102> SK0306090494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0808 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0306090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 3 (YONHAP) -- President Boris Yeltsin 
has promised that Moscow will not conclude any pacts of alliance 
with Pyongyang after the Russia-North Korea Friendship, 
Cooperation and Mutual Assistance Treaty expires in two years, 
South Korean President Kim Yong-sam said Friday. 
  Kim disclosed Yeltsin's pledge during a breakfast meeting 
with South Korean correspondents stationed in the Russian 
capital. 
  Yeltsin made it clear that Moscow will neither renew the 
current treaty nor conclude any others of similar nature, Kim 
said. 
  The Russia-North Korea treaty, which has been the ground for 
relations between the two countries, was concluded in 1961 and 
is due to expire at the end of 1996. It will be extended 
automatically for another five years unless either side 
abrogates it. 
  The core part of this treaty, which calls for automatic 
military intervention by Russia in case of war in Korea, has 
practically become "a dead letter," Kim explained. 
  With regard to possible sanctions against North Korea, 
Yeltsin told him that Russia intends to participate when they 
have become inevitable after the U.N. Security Council took 
necessary steps, including repeated issuance of warnings, Kim 
said. 
  Kim said he was informed of "a top secret" by the Russian 
side in connection with problems related to North Korea's 
development of nuclear weapons, but he could not disclose it at 
this stage. 
  The president said Yeltsin also promised to make a decision 
so that Russia would not sell any weapons or parts to North 
Korea under any circumstances. 
  Commenting on the North Korean lumberjacks fleeing from 
Pyongyang-run Siberian logging camps, Kim said he and Yeltsin 
agreed that Seoul could bring as many to South Korea as it 
wishes. 
  Kim said the Seoul government plans to bring home all 
Koreans 
living in Sakhalin if they so desire. 
  On the shooting down of the Korean Air (KAL) 007 jetliner by 
a Soviet fighter plane in 1983, Kim noted that Yeltsin said the 
responsibility lies with the airline. This is the basic 
official Russian position, Kim said. 
  But he said the two countries will hold working-level 
meetings to discuss the problem of compensating the victims' 
families. 
  As for the development of gas fields in the Russian Far 
East, 
Kim said South Korea and Russia will invest 10 million U.S. 
dollars each to undertake a feasibility study. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

