<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on ROK President Kim's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on ROK President Kim's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on Joint Declaration </H4>

<F P=102> LD0206094194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0905 
GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Nikolay Geronin and </F>
Vladimir Solntsev] 
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Jun -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and 
ROK President Kim Yong-sam "call upon the DPRK, as a signatory 
of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, to strictly and 
consistently fulfil its commitments" under that document, and 
with regard to inspections under the verification agreement with 
the IAEA. This is stated in a Joint Russo-Korean declaration, 
which the leaders of the two countries signed at the end of 
today's summit talks in the Kremlin. 
  Boris Yeltsin, the declaration says, "confirms that Russia, 
alongside other states, will in future also take an active part 
in the efforts of the international community to ensure the 
denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula." 
  President Kim Yong-sam, the document points out, "highly 
appraises Russia's proposal on convening a multilateral 
conference on security and the nuclear-free status of the Korean 
Peninsula." 
  The two leaders agree that "any attempt to manufacture 
nuclear weaponry on the Korean Peninsula poses a serious threat 
to peace and security, not only in Korea, but also in Northeast 
Asia and throughout the world." 

</TEXT>

