<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chinese Air Force General Begins 10-day Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chinese Air Force General Begins 10-day Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206125094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1224 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 2 TASS -- Commander of the air force 
branch of the Chinese People's Army, Colonel-General Cao 
Shuangming, is scheduled to begin a ten-day official visit to 
Russia on Thursday, ITAR-TASS was told by the Russian air force 
press centre. The general should arrive in the evening, at 
20:00 Moscow time. 
  The Chinese commander's itinerary for Friday includes laying 
a wreath at the monument to the unknown soldier and visits to 
the aviation technology demonstration center in Kubinka (south 
of Moscow) and to the victory day memorial on Poklonnaya Hill. 
Later in his visit, Cao Shuangming plans to visit the Gagarin 
air force academy and the Sukhoi experimental design bureau. 
The Chinese commander will visit Volgograd and St. Petersburg 
in addition to spending two days in the Black Sea resort of 
Sochi, where the Russian air force has an exclusive resort. 
  Military experts say that Russia's and China's military 
departments have normal business-like ties. They have an 
agreement on cooperation, which aims to ensure the security of 
the two countries and strengthen peace in the Asia-Pacific 
region. 
  The document, in particular, envisages mutual visits, 
including by the commanding staff. This April, head of the 
General Staff of the Russian army, Colonel-General Mikhail 
Kolesnikov, went to China on an official visit. It is envisaged 
that, by the end of 1994, seven Chinese military delegations of 
different levels will have visited Russia. 
  The Chinese military is especially interested in Russian 
aerospace technology. Russia recently sold China some Su-27 
fighter planes, and additional shipments are under 
consideration. China is interested in obtaining a license to 
produce the Su-27, and has initiated negotiations on what 
conditions such a deal should include. 

</TEXT>

