<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Foreign Ministry Denial on Russian Defense Experts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Foreign Ministry Denial on Russian Defense Experts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206161894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1155 
GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Romanov] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 2 Jun -- A claim by the U.S. magazine U.S. 
NEWS AND WORLD REPORT that several thousand scientists and 
technical specialists from the former USSR are currently working 
to contract in China on the creation of new weapons systems was 
described as "absolutely without foundation" today by a 
representative of the Chinese Foreign Ministry. 
  Replying to a question from ITAR-TASS, the Chinese diplomat 
remarked that reports of Russian weapons experts helping his 
country to modernize its armaments crop up from time to time in 
the U.S. media. He laughed at the magazine's citing of U.S. 
intelligence sources. "U.S. intelligence always gets it wrong," 
he said. 
  On Wednesday, the U.S. magazine's story was denied by a 
senior official from the Russian Foreign Ministry. 
  "I suppose there are some contracts for our technical 
specialists to go to China," he told ITAR-TASS, "but I very much 
doubt their number is as high as that, especially in such a 
delicate and sensitive area of cooperation. I think that it 
does happen, but in single figures." 
  "Thousands of them--that is a crazy figure," ITAR-TASS was 
told on the same day by a qualified source at the Russian 
Federation Foreign Intelligence Service. "Until recently," he 
added, "we had no instances of anybody working in arms 
production." 
  According to other sources, Russian specialists, especially 
in aircraft construction, are attracting great attention from 
Beijing. These are mainly middle-ranking technicians whose pay 
in China would as a rule not exceed 1,000 dollars a month. That 
is considerably less than they would get in the West, but a lot 
more than in Russia. 

</TEXT>

