<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Interview on Bosnia Truce Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Interview on Bosnia Truce Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206204794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2019 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Konstantin Pribytkov] </F>
  [Text] Geneva June 2 TASS -- Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic thinks that the U.N. promoted ceasefire talks on 
Bosnia- Herzegovina, which were scheduled to be held today, can 
be held in Geneva on Friday [3 June]. In an exclusive interview 
with ITAR- TASS, Karadzic expressed the hope that a ceasefire 
agreement can be signed at these talks. "The Serbs, Karadzic 
said, "have been seeking such an agreement for the past two 
years." 
  The talks were cancelled virtually a few minutes before 
their 
scheduled opening today. A decision to this effect was made by 
special U.N. secretary-general's envoy in Yugoslavia Yasushi 
Akashi. He motivated his step by the Bosinan Serbs' failure to 
fulfil their obligation to withdraw troops from a 3-km zone 
around the Moslem enclave of Gorazde. Commenting on the 
situation in Geneva, the Bosnian Serb leader said that the 
Moslem side has once again succeeded in avoiding the talks. 
  The Serb leader surmised that the complications, which have 
cropped up regarding the reported arrival of Serb units in the 
vicinity of Gorazde, can be settled. 
  The Serb delegation intends to take part in the "contact 
group" session on Bosnia of which diplomats of Russia, United 
States, Great Britain, Germany and France are members. The 
session, to which the Moslems and the Croats are also invited, 
is scheduled to be held in the French mission in the European 
department of the U.N. It will resume discussions, which had 
begun at the previous similar meeting held in the French city of 
Talloires at the end of May. The Serb delegation will be led by 
Momcilo Krajisnik, chaiman of the parliament of the republic 
proclaimed by the Bosnian Serbs. 

</TEXT>

