<H3> <TI>   Further on Greek Foreign Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Greek Foreign Minister's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Yeltsin </H4>

<F P=102> LD0306081194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0721 
GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306081194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 3 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- The question of signing 
an agreement between Russia and the European Union [EU] on 
partnership and cooperation was a focal point at a meeting 
between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Greek Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias in Moscow today. 
  At the start of the meeting the Russian president expressed 
amazement that "Russia occupies half of Europe and is still not 
in Europe." The Greek minister stressed that Greece, which is 
the current chairman in the EU's leading bodies, is among those 
countries which actively support the idea of close ties between 
Russia and the EU. 
  Karolos Papoulias invited Boris Yeltsin to the Greek island 
of Kerkira [Corfu] 24-25 June for a meeting between the leaders 
of the EU countries to conclude an agreement between Russia and 
the EU. He gave an assurance that everything is ready for the 
signing of this important document. 

</TEXT>

