<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lukin Says Russia Ready for Agreement With EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lukin Says Russia Ready for Agreement With EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206120394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1147 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Denis Perkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 2 TASS -- Russia is quite ready to sign 
a full-scale and specific agreement on cooperation with the 
European Union, according to Vladimir Lukin, chairman of the 
State Duma Committee for International Affairs. It is still 
early to speak about Russia's membership in the Union but it is 
already necessary to begin a serious preparatory process. 
  Closer economic ties with western Europe is also important 
because Russia may soon join the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade (GATT), Lukin said. Negotiations on this have 
practically entered the home stretch. 
  The agreement with the European Union, according to Lukin, 
must be equitable, correspond to the Russian state's short-term 
and long- term interests and facilitate the provision of equal 
opportunities in trade. This is the only way permitting Russia 
to strengthen its currency and carry out economic reform 
relaying on its own strength. So far the West's readiness for 
equitable partnership in trade is expressed mainly in words and 
as soon as competitive Russian goods hit the international 
markets, the system of quotas and constraints is put in force. 
This approach must be discarded, and specific, realistic and 
tough negotiations should begin, Lukin stressed. 
  The principle of equality should prevail also in the sphere 
of political partnership, Lukin said. Russia has a rich 
experience of "reacting to crises" and is prepared for honest 
cooperation in the settlement in prevention of conflicts in 
Europe, proceeding from both the continental and national 
security interests. 
  Touching on the Bosnian crisis in this context, Lukin spoke 
out against the "ill-considered publicity-oriented airstrike 
policy" and any bloodshed it is fraught with. He stressed the 
need for peace dialogue at the negotiating table by the warring 
parties. 
  As concerns Russia's possible part in the NATO programme 
"Partnership for Peace", Lukin declared that the proposals which 
Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev had taken to Brussels 
took considerable account of the recommendations given him by 
the State Duma and its International Affairs Committee. 
  According to Lukin, it was "an acceptable variant for a 
serious discussion". As regards the outcome of Grachev's 
discussions with the NATO leadership, it is to early to draw 
conclusions because no detailed information on this score has 
been forwarded by the executive to the Russian parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38845 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov107_a_94026" </HT>


