<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Denies Intent To Veto Caspian Oil Development </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Denies Intent To Veto Caspian Oil Development </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206183694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1732 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia has never intended to veto the development of 
Caspian off shore oil deposits, a senior Russian government 
official, responsible for the oil and gaz complex told the Oil 
Information Agency on Thursday. 
  In his words, national interests in the Caspian region will 
be protected by developing the network of export oil pipe-lines 
and by helping Russian companies to consolidate their position 
on oil markets. 
  "Charges that Moscow is striving to dominate or assume some 
exceptional rights to develop Caspian oil deposits are ludicrous 
and disregard one simple fact: the bulk of the oil extracted on 
the shelf will all the same be exported across the territory of 
Russia," the official said. 
  He described as "a campaign coordinated in favour of western 
firms" press reports that Russia is demanding the right to veto 
the Caspian shelf's development. 
  The British newspaper Financial Times has reported with 
reference to Russian government sources that in a confidential 
letter to London Russia's Foreign Ministry made it clear that a 
sanction from Moscow is essential for implementing all Caspian 
shelf projects. 

</TEXT>

