<H3> <TI>   Number of Strikes Rise Tenfold From 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Number of Strikes Rise Tenfold From 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0206112094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 2 Jun 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> MK0206112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed RIA report in the "In Brief" column: "The </F>
Number of Strikes in Russia Is Growing Fast"] 
  [Text] The number of strikes in Russia in the first 
quarter has increased 10.3 times compared to the same time last 
year. They occurred at 288 enterprises, whereas in all of 1993, 
264 concerns were affected. This was announced by Tatyana 
Frolova, secretary of the Federation of Independent Trade Unions 
of Russia [FITUR], who spoke at a session of the FITUR 
Solidarity Action Coordinating Committee. 
  Among the main reasons for the strikes, Frolova cited the 
federal budget's indebtedness, chronic delays in wage payments, 
the absence of a mechanism for mutual settlements, a growth in 
unemployment, and continuous increases in prices for foodstuffs 
and basic goods. Workers' action has been highest in the Komi 
Republic (Vorkuta), western Siberia, and Kemerovo, Tula, and 
Rostov Oblasts. 

</TEXT>

