<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Treasury Says Order on Officer Housing Unfundable </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Treasury Says Order on Officer Housing Unfundable </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0206114394 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 2 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0206114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Own Information report: "Homeless Officer More Dangerous </F>
Than Partisan"] 
  [Text] There are over 7,000 servicemen without apartments 
in Moscow today, most of them senior officers from Defense 
Ministry main and central directorates. 
  In January 1994 Defense Minister Pavel Grachev asked Boris 
Yeltsin to allocate 28 billion rubles to ensure the minimum 
improvement in the provision of housing for high-ranking Moscow 
officers and generals. Yeltsin instructed Premier Viktor 
Chernomyrdin to allocate the required amount. Chernomyrdin 
redirected the document to the Finance Ministry, which told the 
military 20 April 1994 that there is no money for housing. 
  Under the Soviet authorities high-ranking servicemen waited 
for housing in the capital for two years at most. Now there are 
102 generals and admirals alone in Moscow without housing. 
Russia-wide there are 169,700 officers without apartments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38861 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov107_b_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
