<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Rejects Sending Troops to Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Rejects Sending Troops to Abkhazia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206154494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1447 
GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- The Federation Council 
today failed to give its backing to an appeal by the Russian 
president concerning the peacemaking operation in the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict area. This information leaked out 
of the Council chamber where the question is being debated 
behind closed doors today. 
  Boris Yeltsin's letter to the Federation Council stresses 
that the cessation of hostilities in Abkhazia and the signing of 
a cease-fire agreement and on separating the warring sides was 
achieved through the active involvement of Russia. However, the 
situation in the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict area remains 
"explosive". It has become clear that "without the deployment 
of peacemaking troops it is not possible" to effectively monitor 
observation of the agreements and the return of refugees, the 
letter says. 
  The request to conduct peacekeeping operations in Abkhazia 
is 
contained in appeals by Shevardnadze and Ardzinba to the Russian 
Federation president in his capacity as chairman of the Council 
of CIS Heads of State. Boris Yeltsin's opinion is that 
peacekeeping would conform to the UN standards for this kind of 
action. The CIS heads of states' decision will be conveyed to 
the Security Council, which is being offered a UN observers' 
mission with the peacekeeping forces. It is remembered, the 
letter says, that "the basis for the CIS peacekeeping forces 
will be a reinforced contingent of Russian troops deployed at 
units already located in Georgia." 
  Boris Yeltsin said he hopes that the Federation Council 
"will 
support Russia's peacekeeping efforts within the scope of its 
authority." However, according to preliminary figures, when the 
decision was put to the ballot it gained one vote less than the 
required number. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

