<H3> <TI>   Ossetia Edict Seen as Ploy for Talks With Dudayev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ossetia Edict Seen as Ploy for Talks With Dudayev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0306094994 Moscow NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA in Russian 3 
Jun 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0306094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Yakhyya Akiyev article under the "Hotspots" rubric: </F>
"Troops Approach Chechnya Border"] 
  [Excerpts] The tense situation in Ingushetia and North 
Ossetia has made its presence felt again. Admittedly, this time 
it was not through the recurrent exchanges of gunfire on the 
line of the Ingush-Ossetian confrontation, but in a document 
which came into being in the tranquility of Kremlin offices. 
  The Russian president has recently issued the Edict "On 
Implementing a State of Emergency on Part of the Territories of 
the Republic of North Ossetia and the Republic of Ingushetia." 
[passage omitted] 
  The implementation of a state of emergency, as we know, 
entails the stationing of Russian troops on the territories 
which "come under" the edict. A question arises -- what is the 
main purpose of this act, which affects areas of "enhanced 
peace" rather than "enhanced tension"? Maybe the essence of the 
matter is the common border with Chechnya, where, according to 
the presidential edict, Russian Armed Forces have been 
concentrated since 30 May. Naturally, it would be more 
convenient for the Russian president to conduct talks with D. 
Dudayev, the possibility of which people are talking so much 
about, while keeping Groznyy in sight... 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

