Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tatarstan Takes Measures To Stabilize Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tatarstan Takes Measures To Stabilize Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0200165700 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1529 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0200165700 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikolay Sorokin] </F>
  [Text] Kazan June 2 TASS -- "The urgent measures to 
stabilise Tatarstan's economy are being taken for the sake of 
our people," Tatar Prime Minister Mukhammat Sabirov told 
ITAR-TASS. Corresponding draft documents have already been 
drawn up by the republic's government and will be submitted for 
approval to the next session of the Tatarstan Supreme Soviet. 
  "These radical measures were prompted by the difficult 
situation in the republic's economy," the premier said. "The 
production slump equalled to almost 30 per cent this year, as 
compared to the corresponding period of 1993, and the figure for 
the defence industry reached 47 per cent. The situation is 
somewhat better only in the agro-industrial sector, where output 
of goods is growing. Vigorous measures were taken to ensure a 
good harvest this year. The government was able to find money to 
pay the wages delayed since January 1944. 
  "The purpose of the urgent measures is to help the strong 
and 
protect the weak," the premier said. "Strong commodity producers 
will be provided with better conditions for increasing the 
output of high-quality goods. The poor sections of the 
population will get differentiated social protection. 
Possessing rich natural resources and a strong scientific and 
technological potential, Tatarstan is able to create every 
condition for the harmonic development of its market, for 
improving the people's living standards," the prime minister 
believes. 
  "Leading economists and financiers have worked for almost 
one 
year on the urgent measures. They have a minimum programme, 
covering the period from 1994 to 1995, and a maximum programme 
for a longer stretch of time. They have drawn on the experience 
of market economies in more than 60 countries, including Turkey, 
China, Germany and the United States. Although no exact 
all-embracing model was found, many parts of the programme are 
based on foreign experience," Sabirov stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

