<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Complains of Pressure From Moscow, Chisinau </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Complains of Pressure From Moscow, Chisinau </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206174394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1700 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetsky] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 2 June TASS -- The delay in 
handing over Dniester coupons, the unit of local currency, is a 
well-planned action by Moscow and Kishinev with an aim to exert 
pressure upon the Dniester region at the talks on the withdrawal 
of Russia's 14th Army, Dniester leader Igor Smirnov told today a 
meeting of bankers and local government officials in the 
regional capital Tiraspol. 
  Speaker of the Dniester local parliament Grigoriy Marakutsa 
returned on Thursday from a business trip to Moscow, where he 
failed to settle the coupon issue with Russian authorities. The 
coupons were printed late last year at Russia's Goznak mint on 
Tiraspol's order and cost the region 1.5 billion Russian 
roubles. The move was prompted by Moldova's decision to 
introduce its own national currency, the lei, which the Dniester 
authorities refused to recognize and ordered to keep Soviet 
roubles in circulation. This sent inlfation soaring and brought 
the regional economy on the verge of collapse. 
  In addition to it, the situation changed considerably 
following last October's events in Moscow. Seeking not to sour 
relations with Moldova, the Russian leadership decided to hold 
up the transfer of the coupons to Tiraspol. Early this year, 
Russia's supreme arbitration court ruled to satisfy the claim of 
the Dniester region and obliged the manufacturer to hand over 
the coupons to the customer. However, this has not been done so 
far. 
  According to well-informed sources in Tiraspol, Moscow 
demands that the Dniester leadership coordinate its actions with 
Kishinev. The Moldovan authorities believe that Dniester's own 
currency will complicate the process of settlement, which is 
expected to be discussed at next week's round of 
Moldovan-Dniester talks. The talks will be mediated by the 
Russian president's special envoy Vladlen Vasev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

