<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev To Intervene in Government-Parliament Dispute </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nazarbayev To Intervene in Government-Parliament Dispute </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206200194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1635 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 105 (595) by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy and edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Sources close to the head of state told INTERFAX 
that President Nursultan Nazarbayev was drafting a message he 
intended to read to parliament next week on resolving the 
political crisis in the country. 
  The crisis was brought to a head when the Supreme Soviet 
declared it had no confidence in the government's socioeconomic 
and legal policies. The document said that while making noises 
about building a market economy the government essentially 
obstructed the market reform and had triggered an economic chaos 
in the country. Parliament also thought that the government had 
not worked a society consolidating program. 
  To avoid complete paralysis of the authority parliament 
suggested "a constructive dialog between all branches of power 
and public and political organizations leading to a national 
reform program and formation of a government capable of 
implementing the program." 
  A government official told INTERFAX that the government knew 
what to do and was capable of doing it. He said that the 
Tereshchenko government has a specific anti-crisis program that 
was being adapted to the situation in the wake of the 
introduction of a national currency. The official was critical 
of parliament which, he said, had failed to adopt numerous bills 
on oil, transportation and finances and thus obstructed 
investments in the Republic's economy. 
  The press secretary of Tereshchenko described the parliament 
declaration as unconstitutional. In a statement made public in 
Almaty he emphasized that under the Constitution the government 
had to report only to the president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

