<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Officer Warns Against Anti-Russian Actions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Officer Warns Against Anti-Russian Actions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206130294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1150 
GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Vladimir Taranov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- The Russian side will 
not remain aloof and will undertake jointly with the official 
Tajik authorities all the necessary measures in order that those 
guilty of crimes will be punished. This was said at a briefing 
today by Grigoriy Karasin, director of the information and press 
department of the Russian Federation Foreign Ministry, in 
connection with the killing of Colonel Yuriy Shkipkin, deputy 
chief of troops of the Tajikistan Defense Ministry, in Dushanbe. 
  "There is no doubt," he stressed, "that forces that aim at 
further aggravating the situation in the country, which is 
already uneasy as it is, are behind the latest crime. It is no 
accident that first and foremost it is servicemen, especially 
ethnic Russians, who are carrying out their duty to help to 
restore peace and stability in Tajikistan, who are becoming 
victims of these obviously planned terrorist actions. An 
obvious aim can be traced: "To sow uncertainty and fear among 
the population and to provoke enmity between the peoples of 
Russia and Tajikistan," the Russian diplomat noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

