<H3> <TI>   Laar Meets With Japan Trade Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Laar Meets With Japan Trade Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0206120394 Tallinn BNS in English 1823 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0206120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, June 01, BNS -- Estonian Prime Minister 
Mart Laar met in Tallinn today with a delegation from the 
Institute of Mitsui &amp; Co. for Trade and Economic Studies. The 
mission from the institute under the Japanese investment giant 
Mitsui &amp; Co. was led by the institute's President Yoshikatsu 
Hironaka. The visit was due to Mitsui's interest toward the 
economic situation and development opportunities in Estonia as 
well as prospects for the company's operation in the region, the 
government press office says. 
  Laar at the meeting spoke at some length about the country's 
economic policy guidelines and explained that his government had 
based its steps on the principle of radical reform. He said 
that in order to attract someone's attention in the present-day 
world, one had to make steps that may not be common elsewhere. 
  The guests at the meeting praised Estonia's speed in 
proceeding on the reform path. They said the country's resolve 
in introducing a proportional 26-percent income tax was 
impressing. The discussion further focused on the situation in 
the sphere of foreign investments and trade between the two 
countries. The mission members were particularly interested in 
facts about the free trade treaty to be signed between Estonia 
and the European Union soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

