<H3> <TI>   Situation Remains `Tense', Cease-Fire Violations Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation Remains `Tense', Cease-Fire Violations Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0206200794 Yerevan Radio Yerevan in Azeri 1330 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0206200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Radio Yerevan </F>
<F P=105>  Azeri </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Although intensive combat operations have not 
taken place in the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic [NKR], the 
situation in that region is tense. The tension has worsened 
because Azerbaijan's military units continue to fire on the 
Armenian defense positions on various parts of NKR's front line. 
The enemy side violates the agreement for a cease-fire from 
time to time. Obviously, Azerbaijan's Military Command 
Headquarters is unable to control all of its military forces. 
  The Armenian positions in [place-name indistinct], Tauz, and 
Lernak in Mardakertskiy Rayon; Shuraabad, [place-name 
indistinct], and Gyullyudzha in Agdamskiy Rayon; and 
Karakhanbeyli in Fizulinskiy Rayon were fired on with various 
types of arms today. The Armenian side refrained from returning 
the fire. Considering Azerbaijan failed to sign the agreement 
in Moscow to end the confrontation, the NKR Defense Army is 
convinced that enemy units will launch a wide-scale attack very 
soon. Undoubtedly, that will be disastrous for Azerbaijan. 
Furthermore, the international community will realize that 
Azerbaijan's leaders and nationalist circles wish to 
deliberately worsen the situation in the region. [passage 
omitted] 
  No serious incidents occurred on the border between Armenia 
and Azerbaijan until this afternoon. That has been the case for 
the past few days. 
  We wish to hope that the relatively peaceful situation will 
continue to exist and [words indistinct]. 

</TEXT>

