<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier To Announce Government Resignation `Next Week' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier To Announce Government Resignation `Next Week' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206181494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1630 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lithuanian Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius will 
announce his government's resignation at a session of the Seimas 
(republican parliament) next week, he said in the answer to an 
Interfax question at a news conference in Vilnius Thursday. 
  This procedure is defined by the Lithuanian Constitution. 
Under it, the parliament is to confirm the government's powers 
if more than a half of its composition has been reshuffled. 
Otherwise, the government must resign. 
  This situation emerged following the need to introduce three 
new ministers whose offices would be set up in accordance with a 
law on government passed by the Seimas. 
  If Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas asks Slezevicius 
to form a new government again, the present composition will 
remain as it is and only the three new ministers will be added. 
Slezevicius is the chairman of the majority Democratic Labor 
Party in the parliament. 
  This government which has been in power for less than 1.5 
years is the sixth since Lithuania regained independence in 
March 1990. Over this period, Lithuania has achieved a number of 
positive changes such as stabilizing the economy, lower 
inflation and higher standard of living. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

