<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Latvia Seeks To Acquire Abrene Territory From Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Latvia Seeks To Acquire Abrene Territory From Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106194794 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1700 GMT 1 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>
<F P=105>  Latvian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Latvia would like to see the territory of Abrene as 
part of Latvia, as decreed in the Latvian-Russian peace treaty 
of 1920. This was stated at a press conference today devoted to 
Latvia's participation in the Balladur, or European stability, 
pact, by the acting foreign minister, Justice Minister Egils 
Levits. The Estonian and Latvian delegations to the conference 
in Paris on the inauguration of the pact presented a joint 
document on the border question, declaring that the state 
borders of Europe are based on internationally recognized and 
binding treaties. As is known, part of the Abrene district, an 
area of 1,260 square km, was apportioned to Russia in August 
1944. Nine Eastern and Central European countries, which wish 
to join the European Union, have created discussion forums, 
namely the Baltic Table and the Central European Table, at which 
the other interested countries and the European Union will take 
part. The Baltic Table will be attended by the Baltic 
countries, perhaps also Sweden, Denmark, Norway, and the United 
States. 
  Russia will specify issues to be reviewed and will only then 
decide on partciipation at the Baltic Table. 

</TEXT>

