<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Free Trade Agreement With EU Effective Jan 1995 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Free Trade Agreement With EU Effective Jan 1995 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206141094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1101 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The agreements on free trade between Latvia and the 
European Union (work on the text of this agreement was concluded 
on Wednesday in Brussels) is to go into effect January 1, 1995. 
Latvia's State Minister on Foreign Trade Olgerts Pavlovskis who 
reported this at a press conference in Riga Wednesday also 
pointed out that the republic has become the first Baltic state 
which is ready to initial the document. 
  All Baltic states started the negotiations on the conclusion 
of this agreement late February. 
  In Pavlovskis' words, the document can be initialled on June 
20 and then it is to be ratified by the Latvian parliament. 
  In accordance with the agreement, no customs tariffs will be 
imposed on Latvian goods imported to the Western European 
countries. As he said, this regime is valid only for 40% 
of 
Latvia's total foreign trade. However, it does not touch upon 
agricultural products and textile, Latvia's major export goods. 
  Pavlovskis indicated that the agreement has both economic 
and 
political significance because it is a good gesture on the part 
of the Western European countries which view Latvia as an 
integral partner. 

</TEXT>

