<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resolution Against Postponing Election Supported by 201 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resolution Against Postponing Election Supported by 201 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206140394 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1245 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Kiev [no date as received] -- A session of the 
parliament on 2 June examined a resolution "On the Ukrainian 
president's proposal to the Supreme Council on postponement of 
the election of the president of Ukraine, local councils, and 
local council chairmen scheduled for 26 June 1994." The 
resolution says that, taking into account the current 
preparations for the elections, as well as the fact that 
postponement of the election would affect social and economic 
reforms, postponement of the election is deemed inexpedient. 
The resolution instructs the Supreme Council Commission for 
Legal Policy and Legal and Judicial Reform and the Commission 
for State-building, Council Activities, and Self-government to 
submit before 12 June proposals to the parliament regarding 
draft laws regulating the powers of the president of Ukraine, 
the government, and local authorities. [passage omitted] 
  Despite calls from deputies who wanted to make remarks on 
the voting procedure, Oleksandr Tkachenko, first deputy Supreme 
Council chairman (Oleksandr Moroz is informally reported on sick 
leave), put the draft resolution to a vote, and 201 voted to 
adopt it in principle. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

