<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plyushch Calls for Tough Economic Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plyushch Calls for Tough Economic Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206114394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1057 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondent Sergey Kravchenko for </F>
TASS] 
  [Text] Dnepropetrovsk June 2 TASS -- Speaking at an 
election meeting in the mining academy on Thursday, Ivan 
Plyushch, Ukrainian presidential candidate and former parliament 
speaker, called for tough economic measures. 
  "The time for mild decisions has gone. Tough measures are 
need to avoid cruel and repressive ones," he said. 
  Plyushch believes that it is necessary first of all to form 
a 
team of like-minded people in the new parliament to shoulder the 
entire responsibility. He is convinced that to do that there is 
no need to enter into confrontation or reorganise the new 
parliament. It is necessary simply to make competent use of 
those powers which the old one granted to the executive branch, 
he pointed out. 
  The presidential candidate is of the opinion that it does 
not 
basically matter whom the Cabinet of Ministers would be 
accountable to -- the premier or the president. It is important 
that firm executive power be wielded by one body and act 
effectively. 
  Plyushch is confident that in order to get the first sprouts 
of stabilisation now, it is enough to liberalise production, 
including foreign economic activities, reinstate the law on the 
state enterprise, bring into the operation the law on foreign 
activities and foreign investments and see to it that the 
production demonopolisation mechanism begins to operate and the 
law on the banking system is upgraded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

