<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkey's Demirel Visits Gagauz Districts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkey's Demirel Visits Gagauz Districts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206103594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0949 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 2 June TASS -- Turkish President 
Suleyman Demirel, currently paying an official three-day visit 
to Moldavia [Moldova], went today to the southern part of the 
Republic, mostly inhabited by Gagauzs, a people of Turkic 
origin. He is accompanied by President Mircea Snegur and other 
officials. 
  Demirel stated the day before that Turkish businessmen were 
ready to invest in the Moldavian economy. Most of the 
investments will be made in the Gagauz districts. At the same 
time, he expressed his support to the efforts of the Moldavian 
leadership to ensure the Republic's territorial integrity. 
  "We back the negotiations process between the Gagauz 
population and the Moldavian central leadership, intended to 
give our brothers a chance to live on their native land as 
citizens, who respect the territorial integrity of Moldavia and 
enjoy a legal status making for their further development," 
Demirel stated. 
  The Gagauz leaders also pin great hopes on Demirel's visit. 
"This visit will, without a doubt, contribute to the political 
settlement of the Gagauz problem. This will allow us to switch 
over to the solution of our economic problems, to the 
improvement of the people's living standards," ITAR-TASS was 
told by Stepan Topal, the president of Gagauzia. 
  According to the Gagauz leader, the Turkish side is ready to 
help develop telephone services in the Gagauz districts, to 
build roads there, and to re-equip the local processing 
enterprises and other factories. 
  Demirel will sign with Moldavian President Mircea Snegur a 
treaty of friendship and cooperation between the two countries. 
Several agreements on cooperation in the sphere of culture, 
transport services, agriculture, and in combatting crime will 
also be concluded. The heads of the two states are expected to 
decide the terms for large Turkish investments in the Moldavian 
economy. On the last day of the visit Demirel will attend the 
opening of the Turkish Embassy in Moldavia, after which the 
signing of the official documents will take place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

