<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agrarian Party Fails To See Rutskoy as Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agrarian Party Fails To See Rutskoy as Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0506144894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1220 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0506144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Agrarian Party fails to see Aleksandr 
Rutskoy as the united left's candidate in the upcoming 
presidential race. 
  The party's leader Mikhail Lapshin would not place his bet 
on 
Rutskoy even though Rutskoy was in charge of the land reform 
and, more than any other member of the Yeltsin Administration, 
took to heart the needs and concerns of rural Russia. 
  Lapshin told Interfax the party's Council was yet to decide 
who deserved the Agrarians' backing. 
  According to Lapshin, both Rutskoy and his Social-Democratic 
party had to travel a long way before emerging as the leading 
opposition force. Instead of searching for a presidential 
candidate, Lapshin said, the opposition had better bring 
together forces and launch a wide propagandistic and educational 
campaign. The opposition leader, according to Lapshin, would 
appear when his time came. 

</TEXT>

