<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Charges Against Opposition Leaders Dropped </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Charges Against Opposition Leaders Dropped </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306160594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1320 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Moscow prosecutor's office adopted a resolution 
dropping all charges against the opposition leaders who spoke at 
the May 9 meeting in Moscow in accordance with Article 70 of the 
Russian Criminal Code (appeals for violent change of the 
constitutional system). 
  Moscow's deputy prosecutor Yuriy Andreyechev reported to 
Interfax that investigators had found prosecutable crimes in the 
statements of, in particular, former vice president Aleksandr 
Rutskoy, and the leaders of Labor Russia Viktor Anpilov and of 
the National Salvation Front Iliya Konstantinov. 
  At the May 9 meeting in Moscow Rutskoy called for a marking 
of the 50th anniversary of the victory over Nazi Germany with a 
victory over Yeltsin's "anti-popular regime." Rutskoy said in 
the prosecutor's office that he did not mean a coercive 
overthrow of the existing government but called to fight for 
power by constitutional methods. 

</TEXT>

