<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Says Cargo Being Transported to North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Says Cargo Being Transported to North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306220794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1537 
GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ludmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 3 June -- Money has been allocated for cargo 
to northern regions, and the transportation of goods has already 
begun, Vice Prime Minister Sergey Shakhray, who is in charge of 
a commission entrusted to regulate transportation, told 
ITAR-TASS. He said that one trillion rubles over the next two 
months has been allocated for the transportation of cargo. The 
task in this period is to supply only those areas with a limited 
navigation season with only petroleum products, coal, and four 
types of food. 
  According to the State Duma's deputy, parliamentary hearings 
held in April in the two chambers helped to resolve this issue. 
They also showed that a new legislative basis was needed for 
these regions. "Random market relations in the north will not 
produce any good results on their own. State regulatory 
measures are needed," he stressed. 
  The participants in today's hearings in the Federation 
Council on social-economic and cultural issues came to similar 
conclusions, the deputy noted. "Everyone is convinced that the 
transformation to free market relations is a noose around the 
neck of indigenous peoples," he pointed out. Venison and other 
traditional foodstuffs prices have nothing to do with the market 
relations. That is why they need state subsidies. This will be 
less expensive than moving the northerners to towns. Sergey 
Shakhray recalled that in Canada and in Alaska, in spite of the 
market, state regulation of prices is tight. 
  He pointed out that "the development of resources in the 
north is an issue of maintaining the ethnic composition of the 
area." That is why one of the conditions for granting contracts 
for the development of the natural resources will be making 
deductions set by the law for protecting the habitat and forms 
of local economic forms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

