<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Urged To Agree on Abkhazia Peacekeeping </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Urged To Agree on Abkhazia Peacekeeping </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306144194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1320 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin "is likely to use 
some form of persuasion on the upper chamber of the Russian 
parliament in order to force a positive decision on the 
introduction of Russian peacekeepers into Abkhazia during the 
second consideration of this problem by the Federation Council," 
an employee of the presidential administration declared to 
Interfax Friday. 
  He expressed his supposition saying that the refusal to 
support the presidential address regarding forces' introduction 
voiced the day before is "a kind of a gesture, an appeal to the 
presidential team to develop such documents thoroughly." The 
employee has no doubts that the majority of the Federation 
Council understands the need to conduct a peacekeeping operation 
in Transcaucasus. 
  The second consideration of the issue on introduction of 
peacekeepers into Abkhazia in the Federation Council is 
scheduled for June 21. 
  According to an Interfax source, "a slight" delay in the 
introduction of peacekeepers into Abkhazia "is an unpleasant but 
not a fatal fact." He does not predict any threat of resumption 
of a widescale conflict between Georgia and Abkhazia. 

</TEXT>

