<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim, Clinton Speak Over Telephone </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim, Clinton Speak Over Telephone </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0406001194 Seoul YONHAP in English 2353 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0406001194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 3 (YONHAP) -- Presidents Kim Yong-sam 
of South Korea and Bill Clinton of the United States agreed 
Friday that they have no other choice but to press the U.N. 
Security Council [UNSC] to adopt a resolution imposing sanctions 
against North Korea. 
  The agreement came in a 30-minute telephone conversation 
from 
7:15 P.M. Moscow time. The call was made by Clinton in Rome, 
where the U.S. President is attending events commemorating the 
50th anniversary of D-day. 
  President Kim received the call as he wound up his four-day 
state visit to Russia. 
  The United States has completed preparations for a better 
and 
firmer defense of South Korea, Clinton told Kim, according to 
presidential spokesman Chu Ton-sik. 
  Chu said he could not disclose further details of the 
presidential conversation. 
  Prior to talking with Kim, Clinton called Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and told him that the North Korean nuclear row 
will now have to be dealt with by the U.N. Security Council. 
  Details of the Clinton-Yeltsin call were not disclosed 
either, but the U.S. President was understood to have phoned 
Yeltsin in order to secure Russian support for the Security 
Council plans. They also reportedly discussed taking concerted 
steps between the United States and South Korea along with Japan 
and China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

