<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Backing of Non-UN Sanctions Against DPRK Doubted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Backing of Non-UN Sanctions Against DPRK Doubted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606102694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1017 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606102694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Nikolay Geronin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 6 TASS -- A high-ranking Russian foreign 
ministry official hinted on Monday that Russia may not support 
sanctions against North Korea if they are imposed by the United 
States, Japan and South Korea without a UN approval. 
  "Russia, as well as China, has major trade and economic 
interests in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea. That is 
why Moscow will take into consideration its economic interests 
in relations with the DPRK while working out its position 
towards trilateral sanctions against Pyongyang", the official 
told TASS on Monday. 
  However, he added that the common goal of Russia and other 
states is to ensure the nuclear-free status of the Korean 
peninsula and make North Korea observe the nuclear 
non-proliferation regime. 
  The official reiterated the position voiced by President 
Boris Yeltsin that Russia stands for a gradual approach to 
sanctions against Pyongyang and said all other measures are to 
be used first. "Moscow believes that it is necessary to try and 
use all possible political measures without infringing on the 
interests of the sides", the official stressed. 
  He recalled the proposal of the Russian president to convene 
an international conference on security and nuclear-free status 
of the Korean peninsula. "This proposal does not mean that 
other variants of the settlement are brushed aside", he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

