<F P=102>   SK0406055494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0546 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0406055494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 4 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu separated from the presidential entourage 
Saturday and hurried to the United States, where sanctions are 
being discussed against North Korea. South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam, here on a summit visit, instructed Han to go to the 
United States just before he left for Uzbekistan, Kim's aides 
said. 
  Han hopes to stop off in London for special talks with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who is accompanying 
President Bill Clinton on a visit to Europe, the aides said. 
  The U.N. Security Council will begin serious negotiations on 
a sanctions resolution against North Korea from next week, 
setting deadlines and the degree of sanctions to resolve the 
nuclear crisis. 
  Han is expected to fly to New York for talks with U.N. 
Secretary-general Butrus Butrus-Ghali and Security Council 
President Salim Bin Mohammed al-Khussaiby as well as ambassadors 
from the United States, Japan, China and Russia. 
  In Washington, Han will confer with administration officials 
to coordinate policies and future countermeasures on the nuclear 
problem. 

</TEXT>

