<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Optimistic for NATO Meeting in Istanbul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Optimistic for NATO Meeting in Istanbul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306161994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1446 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by Igor Porshnev, </F>
Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others; quotation marks as received] 
  [Text] Moscow hopes that in Istanbul next Friday NATO 
foreign ministers will give their reply to Russia's proposals 
concerning the practical implementation of the Partnership For 
Peace program. Interfax learned this today from Yuriy Ushakov, 
the director of the European Cooperation Department of Russia's 
Foreign Ministry. 
  The North-Atlantic Council for Cooperation will hold its 
routine session on the level of foreign ministers in Istanbul 
next Friday and Saturday. The session will be attended by the 
head of Russian diplomacy, Andrey Kozyrev. On Thursday the 
foreign ministers of NATO countries will have a conference there. 
  As Ushakov said, "Russia stands for strengthening the 
Council 
and for gradually transforming it into an independent agency for 
multilateral politico-military consultations connected with the 
CSCE." 
  According to him, at the session of the Council the foreign 
ministers will adopt a joint statement reflecting their attitude 
to the pressing issues of European and world politics. 
  In Istanbul we'll underscore our willingness to promptly 
begin to work out the possible agreement between Russia and NATO 
on the basis of suggestions [as received] Russia's Defence 
Minister, Pavel Grachev, outlined in Brussels on May 25," 
Ushakov said. 

</TEXT>

