<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgia Claims Russian Forces Transferred to Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Georgia Claims Russian Forces Transferred to Abkhazia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606084794 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
0800 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The following scandalous statement came from Tbilisi 
today: 
  [Correspondent] The transfer of Russian peacekeeping forces 
to take up stations in the Abkhazian conflict zone began today. 
Journalists were told this by the head of the Georgian 
delegation at the Abkhazian-Georgian talks, Dzhaba Ioseliani. 
He stressed the leadership of the Georgian Defense Ministry, 
and in particular the first deputy Russian Defense Minister 
[Colonel-General Georgiy] Kondratyev, guarantee the complete 
safety of refugees returning to Abkhazia. He also noted that 
Russian peace-keeping forces will be active observers of the 
ongoing processes and will actively participate in them. They 
are very resolute and will take the appropriate measures against 
any forces which try to disrupt the agreement achieved. 
  [Announcer] The statement by Dzhaba Ioseliani on the 
introduction of Russian troops to the conflict zone was 
commented on by Petr Shirshov, chairman of the Russian 
Federation Council's Defense Committee, at the request of our 
radio station. 
  [Begin Shirshov recording] Unfortunately I did not hear Mr. 
Shevardnadze's official statement and statements by other 
officials of the soveriegn state of Georgia. Nevertheless I do 
not understand, if this is actually true that the introduction 
of troops between the sides in conflict, between Georgia and 
Abkhazia, has begun today, then this violates the constitution 
of the Russian Federation, no matter who made the decision, no 
matter which top Russian officials. 
  I want to stress that Article 102 of the Constitution, Part 
4, Point G, says that the agreement to the introduction of 
Russian Armed Forces outside the Russian state can be given only 
by the Federation Council. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

