<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   N. Ossetia Under Peacekeepers' Control </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    N. Ossetia Under Peacekeepers' Control </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0506145994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1325 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0506145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz June 5 TASS -- In recent days, the 
situation has become relatively stable in the part of North 
Ossetia where state of emergency rule was extended for another 
two months, from May 31 to July 31. According to military 
sources, no conflicts on ethnic grounds broke out in the zone 
over the past twenty-four hours. Russian peacekeeping troops, 
in close coordination with local law-enforcement bodies, are 
overseeing the state of emergency rule. 
  Officials of federal ministries and agencies continue 
working 
in the region, a spokesman for the North Ossetian president and 
government told TASS on Sunday. They examine the situation in 
the conflict zone and address issues of housing, communications, 
economic facilities in North Ossetia's Prigorodny District, the 
hotbed of the armed conflict. 
  North Ossetian mass media gave on Sunday wide comments on 
the 
statement by the republic's President Akhsarbek Galazov, saying 
the North Ossetian leadership is ready to comply with the 
Russian president's decree on the return of refugees to places 
of their permanent residence. However, the problem of refugees 
should be solved in complex, on the basis of documents signed in 
Kislovodsk. The final word is to be said here by commissions of 
conciliation. 

</TEXT>

