<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pro-Yeltsin Official Elected Mayor of Samara </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pro-Yeltsin Official Elected Mayor of Samara </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606093094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0916 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS Boris Belyakov] </F>
  [Text] Samara, June 6 TASS -- Oleg Sysuyev has been elected 
the mayor of Samara, a major industrial centre on the Volga, in 
the first popular municipal elections of this kind on Sunday. 
Seventy-three per cent of the voters cast their ballots in his 
favour. Sysuyev's closest rival scored ten times fewer votes. 
  Sysuyev was appointed the head of administration of Samara 
by 
Yeltsin's decree two years ago, the Sunday elections gave him 
popular support needed for further work. 
  Although the economic situation of Samara has never been as 
complex as lately, none of the municipal development programmes 
has been aborted under Oleg Sysuyev. The city transport network 
has been renewed and three new underground stations have been 
added to the underground railway system. Housing has been built 
apace, and many hospitals and educational establishments have 
received new equipment. 
  The mayor of Samara pins great hopes on the development of 
partnership relations with the German city of Stuttgart, 
American St. Louis and Bulgarian Stara Zagora. Exchange of 
experience has already involved scientists, doctors, teachers 
and policemen and is likely to do good to the partner cities and 
will help the nations establish better contacts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

