<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Udmurtia Military-Industrial Center Approved </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Udmurtia Military-Industrial Center Approved </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606113094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1052 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Alfred Artamonov] </F>
  [Text] Izhevsk June 6 TASS -- The idea of setting up a 
federal military-industrial centre in Izhevsk was approved by 
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, Aleksandr Volkov, 
head of the Udmurtia Government, said at a meeting today with 
the directors of the republic's largest industrial enterprises. 
The centre's main aim is to preserve scientific, technical, 
personnel and production potential. 
  Udmurtia has a good base for the creation of the centre, it 
was said at the meeting. Factories producing arms and means of 
communications can take the functions of this prestigious body 
upon themselves. The Izhevsk Technical Univerity and the 
Technological Scientific Research Institute "Progress" are 
successfully training personell for the centre. 
  According to the idea's authors, besides defence production 
factories, the federal centre should include structures selling 
military supplies. Enterprise directors emphasised that, in 
order to make the whole complex work on a stable basis, it must 
receive stable military orders with guaranteed payment, 
concessional customs duties on the sale of arms abroad, and a 
temporary exemption from paying exorbitant taxes. The 
enterprises' board of directors also submitted to the government 
a draft, envisaging an investment tax credit to Udmurtia's 
converted enterprises. The credit would be made to the federal 
budget, and would have to be paid back by the enterprises. 

</TEXT>

