<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuril Island Inhabitants Consider Secession </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuril Island Inhabitants Consider Secession </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0506165394 Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks in 
Russian 0600 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0506165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [V. Voropayev video report; from the "Dalniy Vostok" program] </F>
  [Text] Inhabitants of the southern Kuril Islands have sent 
telegrams to the Russian president, the Federal Assembly, and 
the oblast governor outlining their disastrous economic 
situation. A particularly tense situation has developed at the 
Yuzhno-Kurilsk fish processing combine -- Kunashir Island's 
basic enterprise. High prices and astronomic transport costs 
have made Kuril goods completely uncompetitive. The fish 
processing workers expressed a negative attitude towards the 
Federal Kuril Islands Development Program. The Yuzhno-Kurilsk 
fish processing combine strike committee, in signing the 
telegrams, warns that there is a developing opinion among the 
people driven to despair about the expediency of the Kurils' 
secession from Sakhalin Oblast. 
  True, the strike committee did not elaborate further as to 
what the independent islands are going to do and whether this 
will help to improve the lives of the Kuril people. However, 
this is just another indication that neglect of the outlying 
regions' interests by the federal authorities could lead to an 
upset of stability in Russia's Far East. The meeting of the 
Russian Federation Government Commission for Operational Issues, 
on 25 May, noted the danger of the Maritime Kray's economic 
separation from Russia. This is further exacerbated by the 
critical social and economic processes in the Maritime Kray and 
the demographic pressures from neighboring China. As a 
countermeasure, it was proposed to form a commission to prepare 
proposals on the stabilization of the situation in the region 
and prospects for its development in the context of Russia's 
geopolitical interests in the Asia-Pacific region -- this is a 
quote. This is how they express alarm in Moscow over the fate 
of far eastern Russia -- mostly through lip service. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

