<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Commander Adopting `Decisive Measures' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Troop Commander Adopting `Decisive Measures' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0406121894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1036 
GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe, 4 Jun -- The beginning of a well-organized 
and directed campaign of terror against the Russian military 
contingent in Tajikistan was how Lieutenant General Anatoliy 
Chechulin, commander of the Russian border troops in the 
Republic, saw the killing of seven Russians, including five 
senior officers, two of whom were border guards. All the 
murders were committed over a short period, from 31 May to 4 
June. 
  Speaking today at an emergency press conference in Dushanbe, 
the commander declared that the border guard leadership "does 
not intend to tolerate any more blows from behind and is 
adopting the most decisive measures to ensure the armed 
protection of its servicemen both at their duty station and at 
their family residences." Anatoliy Chechulin said that other 
action was also to be taken to ensure the servicemen's personal 
security. Authorized weapons and standard-issue military 
hardware were being made available for the protection of Russian 
citizens. 
  The commander demanded that Tajikistan's law-and-order 
bodies 
should adopt all possible measures to catch the criminals, as 
well as a strict and objective investigation. "The criminals," 
declared Gen. Chechulin, "must be brought to justice for what 
they have done." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39093 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov108_m_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Protect Servicemen in Tajikistan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia To Protect Servicemen in Tajikistan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0406130594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1058 
GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe, 4 Jun -- Russia will take all measures to 
protect Russian servicemen and ethnic Russians living in 
Tajikistan. This was stated at a news conference in Dushanbe 
today by Lieutenant General Anatoliy Chechulin, commander of the 
Russian border troops in Tajikistan, in connection with the 
killing of seven Russians, including five senior officers, two 
of whom were border guards. All these were committed in a short 
period between 31 May and 4 June. 
  Mecheslav Senkevich, Russian ambassador to Tajikistan, and 
Major General Afanasiy Kim, military procurator of the Russian 
border troops, who also took part in the news conference, said 
that the question of adopting measures to protect Russians was 
raised today at an emergency session of the Tajikistan 
Government. 
  In the view of General Chechulin, the killings of the 
Russians mark "the start of the implementation of directions 
issued by leaders of the extremist wing of the armed opposition, 
including Sayed Abdullo Nuri, leader of the so-called 
government-in-exile, who have recently called for acts of 
terrorism against Russian servicemen." Their aim, the commander 
stressed, is to destabilize the situation in Tajikistan, to 
wreck the second round of inter- Tajik talks, and also to 
provoke negative public opinion regarding the desirability of a 
Russian military contingent in Tajikistan. 
  Major General Gennadiy Blinov, first deputy interior 
minister 
of Tajikistan, acknowledged that the acts of terrorism against 
Russian servicemen and ethnic Russian officers serving in 
Tajikistan's national armed forces were planned. The search for 
the criminals is being carried out in close contact with the 
Russian military procuracy, he said. ITAR-TASS has learned that 
three individuals suspected of killing Russian officers have 
already been detained. 
  Having stated that the Russian leadership "does not intend 
to 
tolerate any more blows from behind and is adopting the most 
decisive measures to ensure the armed protection of its 
servicemen," General Chechulin called on Tajikistan's bodies of 
law enforcement to take all measures to catch the criminals and 
to carry out a strict and objective investigation. 
  Russian servicemen will do everything to "protect themselves 
from the threat of banditry from whatever source, using their 
professionalism and the force of their weapons," the commander 
of the Russian border troops in Tajikistan stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39094 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov108_m_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gunmen Adopt Terror Tactics After Russian Army Successes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gunmen Adopt Terror Tactics After Russian Army Successes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0606101394 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 3 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0606101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Anatoliy Stasovskiy under the "Events and </F>
Commentaries" rubric: "Fifth Victim: Is the Opposition in 
Tajikistan Switching to Terror?"] 
  [Text] Alarming and tragic reports continue to come in 
from Tajikistan. Another two servicemen died on the evening of 
1 June. Private Vladislav Maksakov, who was in charge of a 
border detail, was blown up by a mine laid by gunmen in the 9th 
Border Troop Subunit's section. And in Dushanbe, Lieutenant 
Colonel Yuriy Shkipkin, deputy chief of a Tajik Defense Ministry 
troop service, was killed not far from his home. 
  The investigative commissions of the Russian Border Troops 
and the Tajik law-enforcement agencies hardly have time to get 
to the bottom of one tragedy before another occurs. You cannot 
help noticing that attacks on the military have started to occur 
most frequently in the rear services and as a result of 
terrorist and sabotage acts. According to statements by the 
Tajik law-enforcement agencies, the murders of both Lt. Col. 
Vladimir Borisenkov of the Russian Border Troops (31 May) and 
Lt. Col. Yuriy Shkipkin from the Republic's Defense Ministry are 
criminal offenses. And yet it may be supposed with a high 
degree of probability that gunmen are implicated here. The 
opposition has chosen new tactics for waging the struggle. 
Since the failure of several operations actually on the border 
and substantial losses of mojahedin they have switched to 
sabotage and terror. It is perfectly possible that the current 
stepping up of terrorist activity has been prompted by the 
successful Russian Border Troop operation carried out in the 
section covered by the 8th Border Troop Subunit of the Pyandzh 
border detachment (31 May-1 June) to "squeeze" gunmen out of the 
Naychi peninsula: Several dozen mojahedin were forced to take 
to their heels to save themselves after successful joint actions 
by border troops and servicemen of the Russian 201st Division. 
  Five members of the border troops have fallen victim to 
terrorism already this year. Aware that they are losing support 
even among sympathetic strata of the population, the gunmen are 
acting with special savagery, deviousness, and baseness, but by 
no means do all manage to get away scot-free. According to the 
latest ITAR-TASS report, thanks to operational actions carried 
out by investigations and law-enforcement agencies, an 
inhabitant of Tajikistan was arrested 1 June on suspicion of 
murdering Lt. Col. Borisenkov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

