<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Comments on DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Comments on DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0406085294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0841 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0406085294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aboard special plane en route to Tashkent, 4 June 
(YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam said on Saturday [4 June] 
South Korea and the United States stand fully prepared against 
any contingency over the North Korean nuclear question. 
  While meeting with reporters aboard his plane en route to 
Tashkent following his official visit to Russia, President Kim 
said the two countries have a full grasp of all North Korean 
movements through an around-the clock surveillance system. 
  "A war should be forestalled by all means," Kim said. "But, 
South Korea and the United States possess enough force of arms 
to cope with any contingency." 
  The president said he fully discussed in a telephone 
conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton a possible 
sanction against North Korea and the issue of national security 
for 35 minutes on Friday. 
  "Cooperation between our two countries is perfect. I 
understand the telephone conversation between Presidents Clinton 
and Boris Yeltsin, too, was satisfactory," he said. 
  Saying that all things seem going well with regard to the 
issue of taking a sanction against North Korea, President Kim 
said, "Our people may be relieved at conditions that may develop 
over the nuclear issue." 
  He also said President Yeltsin promised not to supply any 
weapons either offensive or defensive to North Korea. 
  "Given the fact that Russia had in the past been the main 
supplier of weapons for North Korea, this pledge of Russia has a 
very important bearing," President Kim said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

