<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karimov Sees ROK Role in Central Asian Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karimov Sees ROK Role in Central Asian Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0506161394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1547 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0506161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Vladimir Nadashkevich </F>
and Vilor Niyazmatov] 
  [Text] Tashkent 5 June -- Uzbek President Islam Karimov 
called his South Korean counterpart Kim Young-sam to cooperate 
in promoting a peace settlement of the Tajik-Afghan conflict. 
  Speaking about prospects for bilateral relations during a 
reception in honor of the high guest, the Uzbek leader stressed 
that all preconditions for these ties had been created during 
the past two years. 
  Encouraging South Korean entrepreneurs to step up 
investments 
in Uzbekistan's key industries, Karimov described Uzbek cotton, 
gold, well-organized chemical and metallurgical industries as 
the best guarantee of their investments. The republic's 
president also belives that Uzbekistan and South Korea could 
closely cooperate in international political issues, for example 
to work for a nuclear- free status for the Central Asian region. 
  In his turn, the South Korean president said he believed in 
the great future of the newly-independent Uzbek state, which is 
to play a key role in Central Asia in the near future. 
  Speaking about over 200,000 ethnic Koreans living in 
Uzbekistan, Kim Young-sam thanked Uzbek people for their warm 
and hearty attitude towards his compatriots. Were it not for 
their assistance, the bitter fate of the Koreans deported from 
the Far East under Josef Stalin's order would have been even 
more tragic, the South Korean leader noted. He said he did not 
worry about his fellow-countrymen living in Uzbekistan. 

</TEXT>

