<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Comments on Russian Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Comments on Russian Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306195694 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] The Russian Federation Council decision 
not to send peacekeeping forces to the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict zone did not go down well in Georgia or in Abkhazia. 
But Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze hopes for a positive 
outcome. 
  [Unidentified Correspondent] The unexpected complications in 
the Russian leadership over deploying peacekeeping forces in the 
Georgian- Abkhazian conflict zone evoked an equivocal reaction 
in Georgia. The opposition to the Georgian leadership, which 
thinks that Russia has no interest in stability in its southern 
neighbor, discerns in this a confirmation of Russia's 
unreliability as a partner. In particular, followers of Former 
President Zviad Gamsakhurdia, demonstrating outside the UN 
representation in Tbilisi against the presence of Russian troops 
in Georgia, organized a protest action against the introduction 
of Russian troops as peacekeepers in the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict zone. 
  The latest complications worry the Georgian leader as well. 
Eduard Shevardnadze had a telephone conversation with Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin on the subject today. In an exclusive 
interview for the Today program, Eduard Shevardnadze said: 
  [Begin Shevardnadze recording] At this point doing anything 
in contradiction to what has been agreed, on which agreement has 
been reached at all levels, would be irrational and unwarranted. 
It seems to me there was no prior explanation. Then, I think 
the Russian leadership understands that a swift settlement of 
the conflict is not only in the interests of Georgia, but of 
Russia as well. An unstable Abkhazia, and an unstable Georgia 
as a whole, are indisputably not conducive to establishing peace 
and order in the North Caucasus. So this is evidently a 
temporary phenomenon, and in a few days I think another decision 
will be made, one that will be conducive to settling the 
conflict. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

