<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma Favors Economic Union With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma Favors Economic Union With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306163594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1412 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy, edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] "I am in favor of economic union with Russia, on 
which we depend so much for energy supplies and a market," the 
presidential candidate and co-chairman of the Interregional 
Reform Alliance Leonid Kuchma told a press conference in Odessa. 
  He said "the non-competitive production of Ukrainian 
enterprises has so far found a market only in the eastern 
republics of the former USSR." However, he said "Ukrainian 
industry is in dire need of western technology, something which 
Russia is unable to give us." 
  Kuchma was convinced that Ukraine needed a strong centrist 
party for the Ukrainian president to lean on. "One possible 
basis" was his own Interregional Reform Alliance, he said. 
  Kuchma believes that only well-versed economists could put 
Ukraine's economic mess right. "I see no one to fit the bill 
among potential future prime ministers," he said. 
  Regarding the situation in Crimea, Kuchma pointed out that 
separatist moods on the peninsula could have been warned 
earlier, without creating a precedent for their encouragement. 
He said that the regions must be given broad economic stability 
rather than political independence. 
  "The Black Sea Fleet is a constant source of tension in 
Crimea," Kuchma commented. "The fleet must be leased in its 
entirety to Russia and the proceeds used to buy Russian oil and 
gas...Ukraine does not need such a huge or, for that matter, 
decrepit fleet," the presidential candidate said. 

</TEXT>

