<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Urges Ratification of CIS Economic Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Committee Urges Ratification of CIS Economic Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306194794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1810 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Federation Council ought to ratify the treaty on 
the CIS Economic Union of 24 September 1993 as this is in 
Russia's interests, the upper chamber of the Russian Parliament 
was advised at hearings Friday. 
  The Russian Government was advised to step up efforts to 
create a free trade area and customs and payments unions in the 
CIS. 
  Federation Council members said that industrial decline 
throughout the CIS was due largely to the break up of economic 
links. 
  The CIS Statistics Committee said that overall economic 
decline in the Commonwealth was characterized by a reduction of 
the gross domestic product on the whole in the CIS by 26% 
over 
the past two years, including by 30% in industry and 
11% in 
agriculture. 
  The Statistics Committee said that industrial output had 
gone 
down by 10-18% in Ukraine, Belarus and Turkmenistan since 
1991, 
24-31% in Russia, Moldova, Kazakhstan and Azerbaijan and 
39-60% in Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, Armenia and Georgia. 
  Sergey Glazyev, who is chairman of the State Duma (lower 
chamber of parliament) Committee for Economic Policy, told the 
Federation Council that the Free Trade Agreement signed on 15 
April this year must be put into effect, all the more so because 
of its benefit for Russia. The CIS market accounted for one 
fifth of Russia's foreign market and it was in the former USSR 
states that Russian goods were most competitive, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39133 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov108_a_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-108 </AU>
