<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   President's Staff See Luzhkov as Next `Master' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President's Staff See Luzhkov as Next `Master' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0406081094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 4 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0406081094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["NG" report under the "In Brief" rubric: "President </F>
Surrenders Positions?"] 
  [Text] As is supposed, Anatoliy Chubays' fate will be 
decided in the next few days. Rather conducive to this also is 
the premier's vacations that he took to save face, and the 
temporary premiership of Oleg Soskovets, who has never been seen 
as being fond of Mr. Chubays, while being closely tied to Mr. 
Luzhkov. The latter's victory must among other things mean the 
end of privatization a la Chubays. One should not, however, 
forget that this privatization was publicly approved by Boris 
Yeltsin at one time. Thus, Luzhkov's victory over Chubays is 
first and foremost a blow at the president and a demonstration 
of the Moscow mayor's absolute power. 
  A NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent heard all of the above 
from a reliable source in the president's staff whose members 
have been of late shedding their loyalty to their present boss 
and pondering on who is going to be their next master. In their 
opinion, the greatest chances belong to the one who is now 
governing Russia's capital in a tough way. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

