<H3> <TI>   Crimean Supreme Soviet Hears Russian State Duma Appeal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Supreme Soviet Hears Russian State Duma Appeal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306144894 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1400 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vladimir Plotnikov from Simferopol; from the </F>
"Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] A session of the Crimean Supreme Soviet today heard 
an appeal from the Russian State Duma which is ready, with 
account having been taken of the whole sensitivity of the 
situation that has come about, to do everything in its power to 
help in the search for constructive compromise on the basis of 
the Russian-Ukrainian Treaty of 1990. 
  For two centuries, reads the appeal, Crimea has served -- 
and will serve, we are convinced of that -- the interests of the 
fraternal peoples of Ukraine and Russia. Also today President 
Yuriy Meshkov said that the CSCE representative put forward a 
similar initiative. 
  As for the talks, they are currently continuing within the 
framework of the joint working commission. The main issue on 
which the consensus is being sought is an international human 
rights bill. The Crimean Supreme Soviet session is also under 
way at the same time. The issue of forming the government has 
been under consideration since the morning. Despite the fact 
that Deputy Prime Minister Yevgeniy Saburov met the deputies' 
requests more than half way, the deputies have, nonetheless, 
adopted not his, but their own draft resolution as the basis. 
The debate was prolonged into the evening hours. 

</TEXT>

