<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks With Crimean Parliamentary Delegation End </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks With Crimean Parliamentary Delegation End </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0406141594 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1300 GMT 
4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Parliamentary delegations from Ukraine and Crimea 
have ended talks in Simferopol on the settlement of the Crimean 
problem. In a final document, the participants noted that 
proposals for coordinating the two sides' legislations should be 
prepared by 15 June. At the same time, the delegations agreed 
that the Ukrainian constitution has supremacy over other laws on 
the territory of Crimea. 
  It was decided to set up a joint working group which will 
deal with the delineation of authorities between Ukrainian and 
Crimean state structures. At the same time amendments will be 
made to Ukrainian laws. 
  The delegation from the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet asked 
President Leonid Kravchuk not to take any measures against the 
Crimean authorities. The Ukrainian delegation also addressed a 
similar request to President Yuriy Meshkov. 
  INTERFAX reports that Oleksandr Moroz, chairman of the 
Ukrainian parliament, plans to arrive in Simferopol on 
Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

