<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Representative on Military Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Representative on Military Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706083594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0815 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 7 TASS -- The armed forces cannot exist 
as one of major elements of Russian statehood without a 
minimally sufficient and steady financing, Major-General 
Vladimir Osadchiy, representative of the Russian Defence 
Ministry, told ITAR-TASS. A military budget to be discussed in 
its second reading at the State Duma hearings on Wednesday may 
become the last one for the army and navy, he stated. 
  Osadchiy said deputies in State Duma factions and committees 
are being intensively coached and calculations by Sergey 
Glazyev, who found additional sources of revenue to finance 
defence spending, are being severely criticised. 
  General Osadchiy believes that Tuesday's press conference of 
Petr Shirshov, chairman of the Federation Council committee on 
security and defence, is to demonstrate the Federation Council's 
stand once again. 
  The Council declared for an increase in military 
expenditure, 
taking into account both inflation and an utter necessity to buy 
hardware and arms, pay money allowance to servicemen, and cater 
for soldiers and seamen. 
  If the State Duma on Wednesday fails to heed the Federation 
Council's recommendations, this military budget may become the 
last one for the armed forces, for they would not be able to 
exist as one of major elements of Russian statehood without a 
minimally sufficient and steady financing, General Osadchiy said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

